## 7. Admin Layer тАФ Mission Control (Under Investigation)

**Candidate:** [openclaw-mission-control](https://github.com/abhi1693/openclaw-mission-control) by `abhi1693`

**What it is:** A full-stack centralized admin platform (Next.js + FastAPI + PostgreSQL) that connects to multiple OpenClaw Gateway instances via WebSocket. Docker Compose native тАФ no Kubernetes dependency.

**Stack:** Next.js frontend (port 3000), Python/FastAPI backend (port 8000), PostgreSQL. Auth via bearer token or Clerk JWT. *(Note: Mission Control is evaluated and rejected тАФ see Section 14. Ports listed are Mission Control's defaults, not KubexClaw assignments.)*

### What It Covers

- **Multi-tenant hierarchy** тАФ org тЖТ board group тЖТ board тЖТ agents тАФ maps well to managing Kubexes
- **Session visibility** тАФ list sessions, view session history, send messages into active sessions via Gateway API
- **Task-level approval workflows** тАФ pending тЖТ approved/rejected lifecycle with SSE real-time streaming and agent notification
- **Agent provisioning & lifecycle** тАФ CRUD agents, heartbeat tracking, SSE state streaming
- **Activity feed** тАФ real-time event streaming filtered by board permissions
- **Metrics** тАФ active agents, tasks in progress, error rate, cycle time with configurable time windows
- **Skills marketplace & agent templates** тАФ centralized skill and identity management
- **Actively maintained** тАФ daily commits, 540+ stars, 826 commits, 5 contributors (as of 2026-02-22)

### Gaps for Our Security-First Architecture

| Gap | Severity | Mitigation Strategy |
|-----|----------|---------------------|
| No kill switch тАФ only delete, no pause/stop | ЁЯФ┤ Critical | Build externally: `docker stop` + secret rotation via our own control script |
| No operation-level policy gating тАФ approvals are task-scoped, not action-scoped | ЁЯФ┤ Critical | Our Policy Engine (Section 2) remains a separate service; Mission Control is UI only |
| No comprehensive audit logging тАФ activity feed tracks task comments, not full agent I/O | ЁЯЯб High | Route all agent output through our I/O Gateway (Section 3) which logs to append-only store |
| Coarse auth model тАФ org-admin or bearer token, no fine-grained RBAC | ЁЯЯб High | Acceptable initially; extend or front with a reverse proxy for RBAC later |
| No cost / token tracking | ЁЯЯа Medium | Add separately via LLM API usage monitoring |
| Gateway integration still stabilizing тАФ open bugs on connectivity (issues #139, #150, #158, #159) | ЁЯЯа Medium | Monitor project; pin to stable release |

### Claworc тАФ Evaluated and Rejected

[Claworc](https://github.com/gluk-w/claworc) was evaluated as a Docker container lifecycle manager to complement Mission Control. **It is architecturally incompatible.**

- Claworc tunnels all instance ports (including Gateway 18789) through internal SSH tunnels
- These tunnels are consumed only by Claworc's own dashboard тАФ no external WebSocket access
- Mission Control requires direct WebSocket connections to each Gateway for orchestration
- No way to combine them without forking Claworc and breaking its security model
- Additionally: project is only 2.5 weeks old (created 2026-02-06), 71 stars, requires Docker socket mount (`/var/run/docker.sock`)

### Proposed Architecture тАФ Kubex Manager + Mission Control

The admin layer is split into three components:

1. **Kubex Manager (built by us)** тАФ thin service using Docker SDK for Kubex lifecycle (create, start, stop, kill, restart). Exposes Gateway ports so Mission Control can connect. Handles secret mounts, network isolation, resource limits. ~200 lines of Python.
2. **Mission Control** тАФ connects to exposed Gateways for agent orchestration, session visibility, task management, and approval workflows.
3. **Security Layer (built by us)** тАФ Policy Engine, audit logging, circuit breakers, kill switch (calls Kubex Manager to stop Kubexes + rotate secrets).

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    ADMIN([Admin User]) --> MC
    ADMIN --> KM

    subgraph admin-layer["KubexClaw Admin Layer"]
        KM[Kubex Manager\nbuilt by us\ncreate ┬╖ start ┬╖ stop ┬╖ kill\nexpose Gateway ports]
        MC[Mission Control\nUI + API\nview sessions ┬╖ manage agents ┬╖ task approvals]
    end

    KM -->|manages Kubexes| K1[Kubex: Email Agent\nGateway :18789]
    KM -->|manages Kubexes| K2[Kubex: Code Agent\nGateway :18790]
    KM -->|manages Kubexes| K3[Kubex: Data Agent\nGateway :18791]

    MC -->|WebSocket RPC| K1
    MC -->|WebSocket RPC| K2
    MC -->|WebSocket RPC| K3

    subgraph security-layer["Security Layer (built by us)"]
        PE[Policy Engine\ndeterministic rules]
        AUDIT[(Append-Only Audit Log)]
        CB[Circuit Breakers]
        KS[Kill Switch\ncalls Kubex Manager]
    end

    K1 & K2 & K3 -->|all outbound actions| PE
    PE --> AUDIT
    CB -.->|threshold exceeded| KS
    KS -.->|docker stop + secret rotation| KM

    style admin-layer fill:#264653,stroke:#fff,color:#fff
    style security-layer fill:#9b2226,stroke:#fff,color:#fff
```

### Kubex Manager тАФ Requirements

The Kubex Manager service needs to:
- Create Kubexes from pinned OpenClaw images with per-agent config
- Assign each Kubex to its own isolated Docker network
- Mount secrets read-only (no env vars)
- Set resource limits (CPU, memory)
- Expose each Kubex's Gateway port (18789) on a unique host port
- Provide REST API for lifecycle operations (start, stop, kill, restart, status)
- Register new Kubexes with Mission Control and Kubex Registry (or provide a discovery endpoint)
- Support emergency kill: stop Kubex + rotate secrets + log the event

### Alternatives Still on Radar

- ~~[**ClawControl**](https://github.com/jakeledwards/ClawControl) тАФ Advertises kill switches and cryptographic execution envelopes. Licensing/open-source status unclear. Worth revisiting if it turns out to be open source.~~ **Evaluated тАФ see Section 14.**
- [**crshdn/mission-control**](https://github.com/crshdn/mission-control) тАФ Lighter alternative (Next.js + SQLite), Kanban task board, AI-assisted planning. Fallback if abhi1693 version proves too unstable.

### Action Items
- [ ] Deploy Mission Control locally via Docker Compose and evaluate hands-on
- [ ] Test Gateway connectivity with a single Kubex
- [ ] Verify session history API returns sufficient detail for monitoring Kubex communications
- [ ] Assess whether approval workflow can be extended or if our Policy Engine fully replaces it
- [ ] Evaluate open bugs (#139, #150, #158, #159) тАФ are they blockers for our use case?
- [ ] Design Kubex Manager REST API schema (endpoints, auth, error handling)
- [ ] Prototype Kubex Manager тАФ Python + Docker SDK, Kubex lifecycle + port mapping
- [ ] Define Kubex discovery mechanism (how Mission Control and Kubex Registry find new Gateways)

